For a weak acid (acetic acid),
$$
\begin{aligned}
K_{a} &=C \alpha^{2} \\
1.8 \times 10^{-5} &=0.4 \times \alpha^{2} \\
\alpha &=\sqrt{\frac{1.8 \times 10^{-5}}{0.4}} \\
&=6.71 \times 10^{-3}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp; \mathrm{NaClO}_4 \rightarrow \mathrm{Na}^{+}+\mathrm{ClO}_4^{-} \\
&amp; \mathrm{NaClO}_3 \rightarrow \mathrm{Na}^{+}+\mathrm{ClO}_3^{-} \\
&amp; \mathrm{NaClO}_2 \rightarrow \mathrm{Na}^{+}+\mathrm{ClO}_2^{-} \\
&amp; \mathrm{NaClO} \rightarrow \mathrm{Na}^{+}+\mathrm{ClO}^{-}
\end{aligned}
$$
In aqueous solution, these compounds decompose into ions. $\mathrm{ClO}_4^{-}$will most easily abstract proton from water molecules. So it will be most acidic.
